t form. This surname is found predominantly in the south and southwestern parts of the country. Compare   Well   1.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>iwil</i>, <i>wil(l)e</i> ‘agreeable, pleasing’."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘tendril’ or ‘creeper’, often used in metaphors describing the slender curvature of eyebrows, arms, hair, swords, lightning, and women's bodies."]}]},{"name":"Eve","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["vernacular form of the name borne in the Bible by the first woman, created from one of Adam's ribs (Genesis 2:22). It derives, via Latin <i>Eva</i>, from Hebrew <i>Havva</i>, which is considered to be a variant of the vocabulary word <i>hayya</i> ‘living’ or ‘animal’. Adam gave names to all the animals (Genesis 2:19–20) and then to his wife, who was ‘the mother of all living’ (Genesis 3:20)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Eve Willis was born in 1490, in Lanarkshire, Scotland as the daughter of Gerhard Will Willis and Mary Barbara Drech. She married Johann Michael Linberger. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1550, in Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1490–1550":"1490–1550","1488–1535":"1488–1535","1535–1640":"1535–1640","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1535":"1535","1488":"1488","1640":"1640","1550":"1550","1490":"1490","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","